OK, it’s time for my own wall of text.

Despite being in conflict with Franklin in game, I tried to step in and split up the fight earlier today fairly, equally, and amicably.  Both sides did unenviable things and they have both acknowledged that.  I don’t know what, if any of it, was tactics, but provoking people in to making mistakes is something allowed in this game, albeit within the rules stated on the H2P pages.  Use of meta is also not allowed and so therefore I can’t buy the whole “I would never play this way if I was X/Y/Z”, even if you suspect you know the player and how they stand on a particular play/issue.  The game is about lying and deceiving and so saying you would never do XYZ is completely allowed, but implying (or players interpreting that) you would never do XYZ because [meta - you know who that player is] is where the line gets fuzzy.  Having said that, you could also use that same meta to argue against exactly that if you are evil and have made a misjudgement or mistake. i.e. they know X would never do Y, so therefore I’m going to use that as an argument as to why I didn’t do that, even though I actually did.  In this case, I am not getting drawn into defending myself against this because it can’t be done without subjecting myself to meta in return, which I won’t (intentionally) do.

Therefore to believe/disbelieve myself/Franklin based on the meta feel of posts is wrong and anything like that should be disregarded from play.  Also to be clear, Franklin has never confirmed who he/she is, and so any inferred meta is in the hands of other players, but remember you may still be incorrect in your assumptions.

I refuse to use meta to win my battles, so if I get lynched wrongly over the stuff said today because people meta-believe a player (Franklin) wouldn’t make a certain move, then so be it.  I’m not going to use meta to counter it.  To clarify, I know Franklin did EXACTLY that move of being too aggressive with his BMC play yesterday and is now trying to backpedal and convince you all by saying that’s something he’d never do.  I had my suspicions on him after yesterday, but his refusal to admit where he actually went and what he did last night secures him as evil for me today.  You lot will just have to make up your minds with what evidence you have and how you wish to judge it.  The play yesterday was (imo) clear evil with no real motivation to help village (i.e. claiming a Seer check and jumping on someone at 8:05 when the Sanguine Horn had just been blown… Not a smart/good play for any Seer imho.).  Follow that up with my stalk on him last night and his denials today and he’s solidly evil for me, even down to “being drunk” last night and accusing his visitors of foul play.  If he doesn’t get lynched today, then I don’t know what else to say.

Poisoned Darts allow you poison a player. After being poisoned, a player has a 50% chance of being roleblocked and a 25% chance of dying. The poison lasts for 3 nights. You have 2 dart(s) left.

A war spear can kill a player at night, but it is heavy and unwieldy so you will roleblock yourself if you choose to use it. It can only be used once. Protection will stop the kill, and if the Huntsman catches you trying to kill someone they are guarding, you will both die.

The Philosopher's Stone is a legendary item long sought by Alchemists. If you hold it for two consecutive nights it will create a random potion. In addition, it will refresh an Alchemist's ability every three nights. Alchemists can hold more than one of their ability potions but can only use one of each type per night.

This armour really is terrible, it's heavy as hell so you won't be able to perform any role actions in the night and it's also full of holes - so it probably doesn't even offer any protection to you from kills. (Spoilers! It doesn't provide any protection at all)
A Potion of Restoration can be used once to recharge a player's limited use abilities (Revivers, Masons, Witches etc)

A Spellbound player will appear as a Witchcraft user and give them an extra sleepwalk action each night
The target will not be notified that they are Spellbound
Spellbound is a visible, persistent and removable aura
